  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Doctor didn’t turn up.&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Disgruntled Dad&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;Orthodontics Dept.

Due to COVID my lad hadn’t had his braces seen to for over 6 months.  
Managed to get the one spare space in the outpatients B car park ( how come the car park is still full when the department is near empty?). Outpatients B Dept was like a ghost town.  I was directed to the usual orthodontics corridor to wait, we were 30 mins early.

After 40 mins with no one else waiting there had been No calls for other patients (usually someone is called every 20 mins), I was getting a bit worried. So I started asking around. Finally an orthodontics Nurse appeared and informed me that the doctor had not turned up and we could either her wait for a couple of hours (when she thought the doctor probably would turn up) or rebook. Unfortunately having taken the afternoon off work, traveled an hour, waited an hour I needed to be back home before the doctor was likely to appear.

The next day I phone the department to rebook appointment and are told nothing is available for over a month. Brilliant! So we wait 6 months, doctor cant be bothered turning up and now have to wait an additional 5 weeks and my lad has to miss school to attend the next appointment.

Why was it so long before Orthodontics appointments restarted after COVID? Dentists have been working for a number of weeks.

Here’s a few suggestions:
- how about some outpatients clinics running 1-9pm, or at weekends, many orthodontics patients are school kids. Why not try to provide a decent customer service.
- put extra clinics on, you have a backlog that needs to clear, you are finishing at 4:00pm!&lt;/CommentText&gt;
